generatePoints

PointDouble[] generatePoints(java.lang.String birdName,
                             int index,
                             boolean oneYear)
                             throws InvalidDataException,
                                    java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
this method reads the your PROCESSED bird data files (that are generated from readWriteAllBirds()) and generates a corresponding array of PointDoubles that will be passed into the Graph class. This method can either generate points showing all the weeks in one given year or focus on one single week for all given years. If the oneYear variable is true, your points include ALL the weeks in the year number=index. If the oneYear variable is false, your points should include only the week number=index for all years in the data set.

Parameters:
birdName - - the name of the bird to study
index - - the week number or the year number to focus on
oneYear - - true means generating points for 52 weeks in 1 year, false means generating points for 1 week over a number of years
Returns:
- an array of points in the form of (x,y) used for the graphing function
Throws:
InvalidDataException - - if the processed data files is not in the correct format
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - - if the index for week/year is not in bounds

plotGraph

void plotGraph(java.lang.String name,
               PointDouble[] points,
               double slope,
               double yInt,
               boolean oneYear)
Instantiates a new Graph class and plots a graph with the given points and regression line. This function should determine the best max/min y values to pass into the graphing function such that all your points are displayed in the graph window. This function should also show the graph once it is done initializing it.

Parameters:
name - - the name of the graph
points - - the array of points to plot on the graph
slope - - the slope of the regression line
yInt - - the y-intercept of the regression line
oneYear - - tells the graph whether it is plotting years or weeks so it can choose the x-axis bounds correctly
